5pt.clickbait: Decision problems in which your choice correlates with something other than its physical consequences (say, because somebody has predicted you very well) can do weird things to some decision theories.

5pv.title: Newcomb's Problem
5pv.clickbait: There are two boxes in front of you, Box A and Box B.  You can take both boxes, or only Box B.  Box A contains $1000.  Box B contains $1,000,000 if and only if Omega predicted you'd take only Box B.

5px.title: Evidential decision theories
5px.clickbait: Theories which hold that the principle of rational choice is "Choose the act that would be the best news, if somebody told you that you'd chosen that act."
5px.text: An "evidential" decision theory (EDT) is one which [action_conditional conditions on possible choices] using standard conditional probabilities, aka [1ly Bayesian updating].  The corresponding candidate for a [principle_of_rational_choice principle of rational choice] would be, "Choose that act which would be the best news, if somebody told you that you'd decided that way."  Contrast [-5n9] and [-58b].  While relatively few decision theorists advocate for EDT as the principle of rational choice, some do.  EDT is historically noteworthy for being the original formulation of the [18v principle of expected utility]--the formula was first written down with the most obvious kind of [action_conditional action-conditional], namely a standard [1rj conditional probability].  However, nobody called this "evidential decision theory" until [-5n9] existed for contrast.  See [58d] for a guide to issues surrounding the choice between evidential and other decision theories (as seen from the stance of [58b LDT]).

5py.title: Prisoner's Dilemma
5py.clickbait: You and an accomplice have been arrested.  Both of you must decide, in isolation, whether to testify against the other prisoner--which subtracts one year from your sentence, and adds two to theirs.

5pz.clickbait: A scenario that would reproduce the ideal payoff matrix of the Prisoner's Dilemma about human beings who care about their public reputation and each other.

5qn.title: Death in Damascus
5qn.clickbait: Death tells you that It is coming for you tomorrow.  You can stay in Damascus or flee to Aleppo.  Whichever decision you actually make is the wrong one.  This gives some decision theories trouble.

5rf.title: Toxoplasmosis dilemma
5rf.clickbait: A parasitic infection, carried by cats, may make humans enjoy petting cats more.  A kitten, now in front of you, isn't infected.  But if you *want* to pet it, you may already be infected.  Do you?

summaries.Summary: The parasite [toxoplasma gondii](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toxoplasmosis) can be transmitted by cats and rats.  *Toxoplasma gondii* can pass from cat feces to rats.  Rats infected by *toxoplasma gondii* are less averse to cat odors, increasing the probability that they will be eaten by cats (which again transmits the parasite to cats).

5ry.title: Transparent Newcomb's Problem
5ry.clickbait: Omega has left behind a transparent Box A containing $1000, and a transparent Box B containing $1,000,000 or nothing.  Box B is full iff Omega thinks you one-box on seeing a full Box B.

summaries.Summary:
A version of [5pv Newcomb's Problem] in which Box B is transparent.  That is:

[5b2 Omega] has presented you with two boxes, Box A which transparently contains \$1,000, and Box B which transparently contains \$0 or \$1,000,000.  You may take either both boxes, or only Box B.  Omega has already filled Box B iff Omega predicted that you would, upon seeing a full Box B, take only Box B.

The Transparent Newcomb's Problem is noteworthy in that [5px evidential decision theory] and [5n9 causal decision theory] agree that a [principle_rational_choice rational] agent should take both boxes; only [58b logical decision agents] leave behind Box A and become rich.  This is an apparent counterexample to a [edt_cdt_dichotomy widespread view] that EDT and CDT divide [5pt Newcomblike problems] between them, with EDT agents accepting 'Why aincha rich?' arguments.

5rz.title: Updateless decision theories
5rz.clickbait: Decision theories that maximize their policies (mappings from sense inputs to actions), rather than using their sense inputs to update their beliefs and then selecting actions.

5s0.title: Parfit's Hitchhiker
5s0.clickbait: You are dying in the desert.  A truck-driver who is very good at reading faces finds you, and offers to drive you into the city if you promise to pay $1,000 on arrival.  You are a selfish rationalist.

5tp.title: Ultimatum Game
5tp.clickbait: A Proposer decides how to split $10 between themselves and the Responder.  The Responder can take what is offered, or refuse, in which case both parties get nothing.

7d6.title: Fair problem class
7d6.clickbait: A problem is 'fair' (according to logical decision theory) when only the results matter and not how we get there.

7ry.title: Coherence theorems
7ry.clickbait: A 'coherence theorem' shows that something bad happens to an agent if its decisions can't be viewed as 'coherent' in some sense. E.g., an inconsistent preference ordering leads to going in circles.
